<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="723" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[95,1301,1514,2257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="723">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[97,350,1514,1547]" pageId="15" pageNumber="723">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 194-210 mm, tail 140-162 mm; weight c.245 g. The Red-hipped Squirrel has a conspicuous red patch on each thigh, and entire underside of tail is vivid red. Nominate subspecies pyrrhomerus has conspicuous reddish patches on thighs, but no red on head; riudonensis also has conspicuous reddish hip patches, but its head is completely red.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="723" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[95,1301,1514,2257]" pageId="15" pageNumber="723">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[97,208,1711,1744]" pageId="15" pageNumber="723">Habitat.</emphasis>
Holes in rocky terrain and similar habitats. The Red-hipped Squirrelis spottily distributed within the landscape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
